Rating: 4
I've made this to rave reviews many times. For the people who thought it turned out bitter, try using a less "oakey" wine. Merlot rather than Cab for example. The oak gets bitter when concentrated in a sauce. Same with white wine sauces. Use Sauvignon Blanc instead of Chardonnay. Hope this helps.

Rating: 0
I have to agree with others who were highly disappointed in the sauce. I used a good Cabernet and it didn't make a difference. There was a strange bitter taste after it reduced and was definitely not worth the effort. It ruined our New Year's Eve steak - yuck!

Rating: 4
I've been looking at this for years, but have been put off by the poor reviews. I took other's suggestions and used a combination of half beef stock and red wine, shallots and garlic. I added some dijon mustard along with only two tbls of cream. I might leave the cream out next time. I finished it off with some red wine vinegar to taste. The result was given high praise by folks. I used horseradish I bought at a local farmers marked that has some much better flavor than the week grocery store stuff so I used less than a tbl but it had a nice horsedradish flavor with out being over powering. If you have been looking at this for a while like I have, I recommend that you try it.

Rating: 3
